n": 771, "end": 778}}, {"id": ["mesh:C061549"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "diaminohydroxypyrimidine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988860487937927, "span": {"begin": 789, "end": 813}}, {"id": ["mesh:C017182"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DAHP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9974479675292969, "span": {"begin": 815, "end": 819}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30158"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BH4", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984288811683655, "span": {"begin": 839, "end": 842}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "bovine aortic endothelial cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8998010754585266, "span": {"begin": 846, "end": 877}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9913"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "bovine", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.6096304655075073, "span": {"begin": 846, "end": 852}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BAECs", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9277672171592712, "span": {"begin": 879, "end": 884}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2643"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GTPCH-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9317407011985779, "span": {"begin": 942, "end": 949}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30158"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BH4", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9856025576591492, "span": {"begin": 960, "end": 963}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10090"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "murine", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9298229813575745, "span": {"begin": 982, "end": 988}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9879328608512878, "span": {"begin": 1028, "end": 1032}}], "text": "As GTPCH-1 is required for BH4 biosynthesis, there is strong biological plausibility for this relationship.  Many studies demonstrated that deletion of GTPCH-1 led to the deficiency of BH4 in endothelial cells. In the hph-1 mouse model, cardiac GTPCH-1 enzymatic activity was reduced by 90% compared to wild-type mice, which led to 60% reduction in BH4 levels (Adlam et al., 2012). In another mouse model of endothelial-targeted deletion of GTPCH-1, BH4 levels in lung, heart and aorta were significantly decreased compared to wild-type mice (Chuaiphichai et al., 2014). GTPCH-1 siRNA significantly reduced GTPCH-1 enzyme activity and BH4 levels in murine sEnd.1 and aortic endothelial cells (Crabtree et al., 2009; Tatham et al., 2009; Wang et al., 2008). The selective GTPCH-1 inhibitor diaminohydroxypyrimidine (DAHP) reduced levels of BH4 in bovine aortic endothelial cells (BAECs) (Wang et al., 2008). Also, transgenic overexpression of GTPCH-1 increased BH4 protein levels in murine hearts and aortas, leading to enhanced eNOS activity (Alp et al., 2003; Carnicer et al., 2012).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:52:36 +0000 2026"}